                  <h5> <a name="gov"></a>Government </h5>
                  <p>As a dependent territory of the United Kingdom, Pitcairn 
                    Island is administered by a Governor who is the British High 
                    Commissioner in New Zealand. The inhabitants of the island 
                    manage their internal affairs through an Island Council of 
                    10 members: four elected (including the Island Magistrate 
                    who acts as chairman and head of the local executive) two 
                    chosen by the elected members, one appointed by the governor, 
                    two advisory members (one appointed by the governor, the other 
                    by the elected members) and one Island Secretary. Elections 
                    for the council are held every year in December but the Island 
                    Magistrate is elected for a three year term. 
                  <h5><a name="res"></a>Resources<br>
                  </h5>
                  <p>The small population of the island subsists on traditional fishing and the farming of fruits and vegetables such as taro, coconuts, beans, bananas, yams, watermelons and citrus fruit. 

<p>The main sources of foreign income are the sale of handicraft and farm products to passing ships, the sale of postage stamps and, in recent years, the sale of honey. 

<p>The territory also receives development grants from Britain.


                  </p>
                  <h5><a name="hist"></a>History </h5>
                  <p>Although archaeologists have found traces of ancient human settlement on the island (including burial sites) they have not been able to determine the date of its origin. 

<p>The first European to spot the island was the midshipman Pitcairn aboard H.M.S. Swallow in 1767. 

                  <p>In January 1790, Fletcher Christian, 8 of his fellow mutineers 
                    from the Bounty , 12 Tahitian women and 6 Tahitian men landed 
                    on the eastern part of the island after having cruised large 
                    expanses of the Pacific searching for a place to hide and 
                    settle. Eighteen years later when the island was visited by 
                    American captain Mayhew Folger, John Adams was the only one 
                    of the original 15 male settlers who was still alive, all 
                    the others having been killed in fights, committing suicide 
                    or dying of disease. The rest of the population consisted 
                    of the 9 remaining women and 19 children. 
                  <p>In 1856, the inhabitants of Pitcairn, who by this time numbered 193, agreed to be transferred to the newly settled Norfolk Island. Several years later, many families, unhappy in their new home, decided to go back to Pitcairn. 

<p>In 1864, the population on the island was just 43. Following the visit of a missionary, the Pitcairners abandoned the Church of England in 1886 to become Seventh Day Adventists. 

<p>The first parliamentary form of government was introduced in 1893, and the present system in 1940. Pitcairn was officially placed under British administration in 1898.





                  <h5>Main Issues </h5>
                  <ul>
										<li> 
											<p>isolation (no airstrip and no regular shipping services)</p>
										</li>
										<li>
											<p>depopulation <br>
											</p>
										</li>
									</ul>
